530. Nec vero supra terram, ‘ and not only on the.surface of the earth is this the case.' There is no verb which can be directly supplied from what has gone before with these words, and ⁴ latet' which follows is of course in itself inapplicable. Some general expressions must be supplied as suggested by the whole context. The omission of ‘ rnodo' where the ‘ sed etiam’ in the following clause of necessity suggests it is not uncommon. So in Greek οὐ sometimes stands alone, without μόνον or ὅπως, before a following ἀλλὰ καί, but chiefly in late Greek.
